  "doc_id": "51420",
  "text": "Thus, it is clear that adoption has permeated and continues to permeate and penetrate our history and society. Indeed, one is now highly likely to encounter someone who is an adoptive triad member, whether an adoptee, an adoptive parent, or a birth parent. According to some estimates, between 40 million [CITATION_1] and 100 million (www.adoptioninfor mationinstitute.org) Americans are directly affected by adoption in very fundamental ways. And these adoptees come from many parts of the world, particularly from several countries in South and Central America, Korea, China, and Russia, as discussed by Baden (Chapter 8), Camacho-Gingerich, Branco-Rodriguez, Pitteri and Javier (Chapter 10), and McGinnis (Chapter 11). Thus, questions such as what are the psychological, socioeconomic, sociopolitical, and legal challenges facing adopted persons, birth parents, and adoptive parents become even more complex when considering the different cultural, racial, sociopolitical, ecological, and linguistic backgrounds that triad members may bring to the adoption equation. The ramifications of these factors cannot be underestimated considering that approximately 8% of all adoptions are transracial and that the numbers of international adoptions have more than doubled from 1992 to 1999 [CITATION_2] .",
